  <title type="text">Story/Meta-Story</title>
  <link rel="alternate" href="http://stephenfoster.us/2019/10/story-meta-story.html?utm_source=all&amp;utm_medium=Atom" />
  <id>urn:http-stephenfoster-us:-2019-10-story-meta-story-html</id>
  <published>2019-10-10T14:32:25Z</published>
  <updated>2019-10-10T14:32:25Z</updated>
  <author>
   <name>Stephen R. Foster</name></author>
  <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="/img/posts/2019-10-10-story-meta-story/pict.png" alt="image" height="251" style="vertical-align: -10px; margin: -3px -3px -3px -3px;" width="251" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Consider learning that an ancient tome you found in a used bookstore was written as its author slowly went insane.
Knowing this would change the experience of reading that book!  I, for one, would like to know such &lt;span style="font-weight: bold"&gt;meta-stories&lt;/span&gt; up front.  Some might prefer to learn it afterward.  But I think we can all agree that knowing the &lt;span style="font-weight: bold"&gt;meta-stories&lt;/span&gt; at &lt;span style="font-style: italic"&gt;some&lt;/span&gt; point generally enhances the reading experience.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;a href="http://stephenfoster.us/2019/10/story-meta-story.html?utm_source=all&amp;amp;utm_medium=Atom"&gt;&lt;em&gt;More&amp;hellip;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</content></entry>
